1.1 – The OSI Model:-

## Purpose:
The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model is a 7-layer conceptual framework used to describe how data moves across a network.
The 7 Layers (Top → Bottom):

| Layer | Name         | Key Responsibility                 |
| ----- | ------------ | ---------------------------------- |
| 7     | Application  | User-facing network services       |
| 6     | Presentation | Encryption, formatting             |
| 5     | Session      | Session establishment & management |
| 4     | Transport    | End-to-end delivery (TCP/UDP)      |
| 3     | Network      | Logical addressing (IP routing)    |
| 2     | Data Link    | MAC addressing, framing            |
| 1     | Physical     | Bits, cables, signaling            |

## Encapsulation Process:
Data is wrapped with headers as it moves down the stack:
Application → Transport → Network → Data Link → Physical

1.2 – Network Appliances and Applications:-

## Networking Devices:
### Switch:
* Operates at Layer 2
* Forwards frames based on MAC address table

### Router:
* Operates at Layer 3
* Routes packets between networks using IP addresses

### Firewall:
* Filters traffic based on rules
* Can operate at L3–L7 depending on type

### Access Point (AP):
* Connects wireless clients to wired LAN

### Other Devices:
* Load balancer
* IDS/IPS
* Proxy server

## Networking Functions:-

### VPN (Virtual Private Network):
Encrypted tunnel across public networks.

### CDN (Content Delivery Network):
Distributed content caching for performance.

### QoS (Quality of Service):
Traffic prioritization mechanism.

### IP (Internet Protocol):
Provides logical addressing and routing.

